<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Prosecutors had long hoped Mathew Martoma, a former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors, would provide the missing link in their pursuit of the hedge fundâs owner, Steven A. Cohen. Instead, the insider trading case prosecutors never thought would happen is going to trial, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/trial-to-begin-for-ex-sac-trader-who-cut-no-deal/"><b>Matthew Goldstein and Ben Protess write in DealBook</b></a>. Prosecutors first confronted Mr. Martoma in November 2011, asking him to cooperate in their long-running investigation of Mr. Cohen, and they have continued to press him in a number of meetings since. But Mr. Martoma has baffled officials by refusing to cooperate against the boss who fired him in 2010.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jury selection is set to begin Tuesday in federal court in Lower Manhattan, where prosecutors are undefeated in insider trading cases under the United States attorney in Manhattan, Preet Bharara.</p>

<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The indictment accuses Mr. Martoma of obtaining secret information from a doctor on clinical trials for Alzheimerâs drugs, leading to trades that directly involved Mr. Cohen and resulting in profits and avoided losses totaling $276 million during the height of the financial crisis. If convicted, Mr. Martoma faces up to 45 years in prison, away from his wife and three young children.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Prosecutors contend Mr. Martoma formed a relationship with Dr. Sidney Gilman, a retired professor who was a paid consultant for Elan, one of two companies developing the Alzheimer drug. They claim Dr. Gilman shared confidential information on the drug with Mr. Martoma, who then spoke by phone to Mr. Cohen shortly before SAC âsold virtually allâ of its stake in Elan and Wyeth, another drug company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Goldstein and Mr. Protess write: âComing on the heels of last monthâs insider trading conviction of another SAC employee, Michael S. Steinberg, and SACâs guilty plea in November to insider trading charges, the trial could become yet another embarrassing episode for Mr. Cohen and his hedge fund.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The case against Mr. Martoma was built in part on interviews and depositions by federal authorities with more than a dozen of his former hedge fund colleagues, according to a recent court filing, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/sac-traders-co-workers-were-deposed/">Mr. Goldstein reports.</a></b> Prosecutors could call several of the former SAC traders and analysts they interviewed as witnesses during the trial. Mr. Cohen himself is not expected to be called.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While prosecutors have won convictions in a number of prominent insider trading cases, the case against Mr. Martoma is the most significant because of the dollar amount traded and the involvement of Mr. Cohen, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/broad-strokes-vs-pinpoint-in-martoma-trial/"><b>Peter J. Henning writes in the White Collar Watch column</b></a>. <b>Prosecutors are pulling out all the stops,</b> including using a loophole that permits the use of circumstantial evidence to introduce Mr. Martomaâs pattern of bad acts related to seeking inside information on other drug trials.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">CHANGED VIEW OF ACTIVIST INVESTORS <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Once seen as barbarians pushing to change corporate America through brute force, activist investors are now often seen as a good thing, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/no-barbarians-at-the-gate-instead-a-force-for-change/">Alexandra Stevenson writes in DealBook.</a></b> Indeed, Mary Jo White, the Securities and Exchange Commission chairwoman, said during a December conference that while the activist label once had a negative connotation, this view âis not necessarily the current view and it is certainly not the only view.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Stevenson writes: âThe beneficiaries of this new attitude are activist hedge fund managers <b>like David Einhorn and Daniel S. Loeb,</b> who last year rattled the corporate boards of some of Americaâs biggest and best-known companies. They are beginning the new year with swelling coffers and more public support than ever before.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as the industry suffered unimpressive returns, some activist hedge funds managed to outperform the soaring stock market last year, spurring investors to show their support by pouring an estimated $10 billion to $12 billion of new money into the fundsâ war chests and bringing their total to more than $100 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Successful campaigns helped generate this increased level of support, including attempts to press Apple to return cash to shareholders and a push to shake up management at Microsoft. And at a time when companies are sitting on record levels of cash and regulators are focusing on corporate government issues, these activist investors are especially appealing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Gregory P. Taxin, president of the $1.5 billion hedge fund Clinton Group, said: <b>âThe brute force of ownership is not required anymore</b> because the big institutional players listen to both sides and are willing to back the activist fund if they believe in them.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">A CORPORATE VERSION OF âHOT OR NOTâ <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> âCall it the âC.E.O.â beauty premium,ââ <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/never-mind-the-rsum-how-hot-is-the-c-e-o/?_r=0">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column.</a> </b> A study run by two economists may show that investors assign higher share values to companies run by attractive chief executives, who are paid more than their less-attractive counterparts and are better at sealing financially successful deals. âThe conclusion of the unusual academic study â a sort of corporate version of &#8216;Hot or Not&#8217; â is that <b>shareholders are as easily swayed by the glint in the eye of a chief executive as they are by a companyâs actual numbers,</b> at least in the short term.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The <b>International Trade Balance</b> report for November is out at 8:30 a.m. <b>Jury selection begins</b> in the trial against Mathew Martoma, the former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors accused of insider trading. Two regional Federal Reserve presidents discuss the economic outlook: <b>Eric S. Rosengren</b>, the president of the Boston Fed, is at the podium at 8:30 a.m. in Hartford, and <b>John C. Williams</b>, the president of San Francisco Fed, takes the stage in Phoenix at 2:10 p.m.</p>
